Unrestrained Central Bank Governors?
Prague—Recently, one-sided criticism of central banks in developed countries has become fashionable.
The main points of criticism are roughly as follows: since 2008, monetary policymakers have been too active, their authority has expanded too quickly, and they are harming the economy.
This claim—strangely, it is popular among ideologically incongruent camps, such as liberals and neo-Marxists—is completely wrong.
Critics have failed to understand that modern central banks are not only responsible for curbing inflation, but also for maintaining long-term price stability.
The level of prices is like a person's body temperature, which can fluctuate within a range that is neither too high nor too low without causing serious symptoms.
When combating deflation caused by weak demand and containing high inflation driven by excessive demand, central banks must be equally "active".
Although the battle is entirely symmetrical, the public's assessment of it is inexplicably severely biased, especially in countries where people are financially very conservative.
This includes my homeland, the Czech Republic. Czech savers have very small savings, and the loan-deposit ratio is still far below 100%.
Czechs worry about inflation, even though the Czech inflation rate reached a 13-year low last year, and the Czech National Bank, which I have served as deputy governor since 2013, has been committed to eliminating deflation risks.
Other common complaints about the policies of central banks in developed countries since 2008 are that these policies have caused redistributive effects.
Of course they do, but so what?
Any monetary policy action redistributes wealth.
Raising interest rates makes savers happy, while cutting interest rates benefits borrowers.
Importers prefer a strong exchange rate; exporters prefer a weak exchange rate.
For monetary policy to be effective, it must have different impacts on different groups at different times.
This is not a mistake; this is the nature of monetary policy.
Some critics also say that central banks have failed to achieve inflation targets in any case, so their activism is not only unnecessary but also ineffective.
Sometimes they even place these contradictory criticisms in one sentence, as if they were accusing someone of shooting blanks yet causing casualties.
The reality is that central banks around the world successfully maintained price stability and the purchasing power of money during and after the global financial crisis — and it was an outstanding success without any doubt.
If it were not for their intervention, their economies would have faced catastrophic deflation, a sharp drop in asset prices, and a complete collapse of the financial and real sectors.
Clearly, strong action was the right approach to deal with the crisis (what role central banks played in the outbreak of the financial crisis is another issue).
In a system using a flexible currency without intrinsic value, the quantity of money must change over time in order for the purchasing power of money to remain roughly constant.
Therefore, price stability, rather than the quantity of money, is the important issue.
The expansion of central bank balance sheets reflects the depth of the problems faced by many economies after 2008.
Against this background, central banks have taken necessary measures to maintain purchasing power and price stability.
For them, there is no such thing as "activism"; there is only the eternal mission that needs to be fulfilled.
If you find this assertion arrogant, let me provide some evidence.
People vote with their wallets.
If their money's purchasing power was severely damaged after 2008, they would naturally seek to exchange their currency (for other currencies, precious metals, or other forms of savings).
This is rare in the developed world.
Of course, many central banks have not met their inflation targets.
(Central banks typically define the ideal "temperature" of the economy as an annual inflation rate of around 2%.
) This is certainly unpleasant, but it does not lead to catastrophe, especially considering that falling prices are partly due to supply — rather than demand — shocks, such as a sharp drop in oil prices.
This shock benefits consumers and poses no threat to price stability, at least for net oil importing countries.
Consider this scenario.
A company plans to increase its sales by 2%, but the manager achieves this only by increasing it by 1% each year for two consecutive years.
Would you consider this company a failure?
Probably not.
After all, private companies often experience deviations of 10% or more between planned and actual profits and revenues.
Most businesses have fewer variables in their operating environments than central banks.
If that is the case, how can you expect central banks to always achieve precise inflation targets regardless of the economic environment?
It must be clarified that I am not saying central banks should not strive to work closely toward their targets.
They absolutely should do so.
Moreover, they absolutely should not allow inflation expectations to become unstable.
However, when judging central banks, people need to maintain proper restraint.
They indeed need to stop saying untrue things — such as, the central bank's policy arsenal is not only potentially exhausted, but has already approached exhaustion.
Monetary policymakers have ample weapons and unlimited ammunition at their disposal to use freely.
These weapons vary in caliber and their effectiveness differs at different times.
Not all weapons are suitable for all situations in all economies.
However, the ability of central banks to create and destroy money is theoretically unlimited.
Central bank governors should tell their critics, who are ignorant, "Enough!"
None of our critics have been able to explain clearly and convincingly why price stability is the wrong goal, what key goal central banks should pursue, and what completely different approach they should have taken since 2008.
There is a very simple reason for this: the policy adopted by central banks in developed countries since the crisis was the correct policy.
In fact, this policy pulled our economies back from the brink.
You're welcome.
